{"cursor":"10028","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" studio in 2010. In the background are the station owner Fazle Karim Fazl, with\n former U.S. Ambassador Karl Eikenberry and Afghan Communications Minister\n Sangin Amirzai.]] 'Television in Afghanistan' was first introduced in 1964,\n when a new organization called Radio Television Afghanistan (government-owned)\n founded two channels: RTA and Afghanistan National Television. After the\n completion of feasibility study under grant aid from Japan, construction work\n of the studio and transmitter buildings were finished by August 1978.\n\nDuring the Taliban rule between 1996 and 2001, television was strictly banned\nbut RTA was the sole TV channel in the country since then. Anyone owning or\nwatching TV was arrested and punished. Store were not allowed to sell TVs,\nsatellite dishes, VCRs, DVD players, or video cameras. When the Karzai\nadministration came to power in December 2001, television service was re-\nintroduced. RTA and Afghanistan National Television channels were launched again\nin 2002, after Germans built their headquarters in Kabul. It was reported in\n2011 that as many as 76 television channels are available in Afghanistan, 36 of\nthem in the capital of Kabul. They are broadcasting news, entertainment,\nreligious, sports and cultural programs with each channel having its own\nviewers. http://www.wakht.af/index.php?option=com_cont-\nent&view=article&id=3777%3Ajournalists-ask-nds-to-present-accusation-evidences-\nto-justice&catid=18%3Aculture&Itemid=26&lang=en\n","linknr":316,"url":"Afghan_Television","recorded":1375055931,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Television_in_Afghanistan&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Television_in_Afghanistan&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Television_in_Afghanistan